Exciting, I didn’t know these were already called out in FIRST -controlled code…

posts.name: Mr. Siefen | 453
posts.cooked: @R.C what aren’t you telling us!!! /S We know you saw this now!

posts.name: Vaughn Khouri
posts.cooked:
Haha I haven’t seen anything, only heard rumors. That being said, I feel one can kind of put 2 and 2 together:

The Kraken is an incredibly powerful motor, but it’s also super large, heavy, and expensive. Though it’s an incredible product for the money, there are applications where a 775-class motor just makes more sense. One look at the pocketing on 1323s robot and you’ll see why they might want a lighter alternative…

CTRE clearly likes their ecosystem, but V6 doesn’t support the brushed motor controllers at all . They’re apparently  moving away from brushed motors, so they’ll want to have an equivalent replacement. This also makes a lot of sense when you consider SwerveXS, which is marketed as using a 775…but I really don’t think teams will want to do this because of the compatibility issues with CTRE swerve generator.

Aside from being a clear open market segment, it’s also not really hard to compete (although redux could change this). The 550 has never really been ideal, ever since it was introduced:

Free speed way too high to be useable without a UP or VP

Tiny output shaft is really impractical

Will smoke itself if it stalls for more then a few seconds unless super conservative current limits are set (which they aren’t by default)

No integrated controller

Has to use a spark max, which is practically the size of the motor itself, and has to be placed nearby; which makes the whole package larger then a Neo or Kraken class motor anyway

Redux just proved you can fit a 2 inch bolt circle and integrated controller nicely on a 775 size motor, which was one of the main feasibility concerns people had

So given this, I’d be really surprised if we don’t get a Kraken X30 type thing in the next year or two - and I’d bet on it being a huge success.

Now RC, if you’re reading this, hopefully I’m not completely wrong
